 history of Puerto Rico that gives voice to the archipelago’s people while offering a lens through which to understand the political, economic, and social challenges confronting them today.In this masterful work of scholarship, Meléndez-Badillo sheds light on the vibrant cultures of the archipelago in the centuries before the arrival of Columbus and captures the full sweep of Puerto Rico’s turbulent history in the centuries that followed, from the first indigenous insurrection against colonial rule in 1511—led by the powerful chieftain Agüeybaná II—to the establishment of the Commonwealth in 1952. He deftly portrays the contemporary period and the intertwined though unequal histories of the archipelago and the continental United States.Puerto Rico is an engaging, sometimes personal, and consistently surprising history of colonialism, revolt, and the creation of a national identity, offering new perspectives not only on Puerto Rico and the Caribbean but on the United States and the Atlantic world more broadly.Available in Spanish from our partners at Grupo Planeta  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aHISTORY / Caribbean & West Indies / General.2bisacsh  aBad Bunny.  aBoriken.  aCalle 13.  aCaribbean.  aCold War Latin America.  aHistory of Puerto Rico: Puerto Rican history.  aHistory.  aHurricane Maria.  aJorell Meléndez-Badillo.  aLatin America.  aLatinx.  aNuyorican.  aPR Day.  aPrinceton University Press.  aPuerto Rico Day.  aPuerto Rico.  aRcky Martin.  aSpanish.  aTelegramgate.  aboricua.  acolonialism.  acurrent events.  aenslaved revolts.  aimperialism.  aindigenous history.  anation-building.  anational history.  aneoliberalism.  apolitics.  apopular protests.  aresistance.  arevolution.  asilvia rivera.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruytert